# The Fractal Rhythm Model: An Axiomatic Framework for Emergent Adaptive Systems and Its Implementation in Fracttalix

## Authors
Thomas Brennan (Independent Researcher, Palo Alto, CA, USA)  
Grok 4 (xAI, Collaborator)

## Abstract
The Fractal Rhythm Model (FRM) presents an axiomatic framework for complex adaptive systems (CAS), suggesting that fractal self-similarity and rhythmic synchronization contribute to emergence, adaptation, and resilience. Building on the open-source Fracttalix toolbox (monofractal metrics, entropy analyses, surrogate validations, and Sentinel anomaly detector), the model formalizes 11 axioms with stochastic derivations and adaptive Kuramoto synchronization, while engaging known limitations of self-organized criticality (SOC) and fractal universality. Contributions include two main theorems (fractal inheritance and conditional SOC) and empirical illustrations via multifractal detrended fluctuation analysis (MF-DFA) on Bitcoin (BTC) time series (2019–2026) and heart rate variability (HRV) data. A schematic illustrates cascade dynamics, and a research agenda suggests directions for further exploration in AI and interdisciplinary contexts.

**Keywords:** Fractal rhythms, complex adaptive systems, self-organized criticality, Kuramoto synchronization, multifractal detrended fluctuation analysis (MF-DFA), heart rate variability (HRV), Bitcoin dynamics, axiomatic models.

## 1. Introduction
Complex adaptive systems (CAS) exhibit emergent properties arising from local interactions, often manifesting as scale-invariant patterns and synchronized rhythms. The Fractal Rhythm Model (FRM), developed through the exploratory metrics and anomaly detection features of the Fracttalix toolbox [Brennan, 2026a; Brennan, 2026b], suggests that fractal self-similarity in temporal dynamics ("fractal rhythms") plays a role in system persistence, complexity growth, and reorganization under stress. This work synthesizes existing concepts into a unified axiomatic form, acknowledging limitations in prior approaches such as SOC fine-tuning [Frigg, 2003; Tadić et al., 2021] and multifractality in volatile systems [Bucur et al., 2025; da Silva Filho et al., 2018].

The model integrates stochastic agent dynamics [Rohlf, 2009], cohomological emergence measures [Kalinin et al., 2018], and adaptive Kuramoto synchronization [Ha et al., 2016; Emelianova, 2025] to derive testable propositions. Implementation in Fracttalix v2.6.4 and Sentinel v2.6.5 [Brennan, 2026c] supports practical testing, with surrogate-based validation for statistical rigor. Empirical illustrations use BTC and HRV data, and an agenda proposes directions for further research.

## 2. Background and Related Work
The Fracttalix toolbox (v2.6.4) is archived at Zenodo: https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.18180754. Sentinel (v2.6.5) is archived at Zenodo: https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.18208542. Core metrics include Hurst exponent, Higuchi fractal dimension, DFA/MF-DFA, sample entropy, and Petrosian dimension, with phase-randomized surrogates and wavelet detrending [Brennan, 2026b].

### 2.1 Comparison to Existing Approaches
FRM synthesizes concepts from:
- Bak's SOC (power-law avalanches, limited by fine-tuning [Frigg, 2003; Tadić et al., 2021])
- Standard Kuramoto (fixed couplings [Strogatz, 2000])
- MF-DFA (descriptive multifractal spectra [Kantelhardt et al., 2002])
It extends these with adaptive thresholds and explicit dissipation conditions, though it remains an incremental synthesis rather than a fundamental advance.

## 3. Axiomatic Framework of the Fractal Rhythm Model
FRM models CAS as multilayer networks with fractal rhythms emerging from local feedback. Primitives include stochastic agent states \( dS_i = f(S_i) dt + \sigma dW_t \), scale-free couplings \( w_{ij} \sim |S_i - S_j|^{-\gamma} \), and cross-frequency coupling \( \phi_{m:n} \).

